[4] New Zealand (North Island)
Date: Wed 17 Sep 2014
Source: ONE News [summ., edited]
http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/measles-outbreak-over-after-281-cases-6083725


Measles outbreak over after 281 cases
-------------------------------------
The measles outbreak in the North Island has been declared over. There have been 281 confirmed measles cases across the North Island since December [2013], with 15 percent of the cases requiring hospital treatment, said Associate Health Minister Jo Goodhew. The outbreak mainly hit the Waikato and Auckland regions. Public Health Units in the affected regions have been working hard to halt the spread of this highly infectious virus, says Ms Goodhew.

This has included quarantining unimmunised people who have been exposed to the measles virus, promoting immunisation and raising awareness of the symptoms and seriousness of measles. "However, with outbreaks of measles still occurring overseas, we cannot be complacent. The current outbreak began from New Zealanders returning from overseas where they had contracted measles, so we know that it can easily occur again," Ms Goodhew says. As immunisation continues to be the best form of protection, people should check their immunisation status, and get themselves and their families immunised against measles as soon as possible, she says.

